Waffle irons and the Willamette Valley. Patchouli and performance. This was the spirit of Eugene, Oregon in the 1970s. During this time, Nike was evolving and innovating rapidly which meant its graphic identity was too—especially on the t-shirt side of the hustle. Tees were the easiest way to communicate the brand’s rapidly developing identity. What’s most notable about these tees is that their bohemian, PNW-inspired look still influences much of the graphic work you still see in today’s designs.

Which one of these tees are you building a fit around? 

These original graphic tees were provided by the Department of Nike Archives.

Like the teams they love and support, every fan has their own unique style. 

From getting kitted out like the athletes on the pitch to making their colors their own 🌏, there’s no one way to represent your squad. And that’s what makes the beautiful game forever inspiring ✨ #NikeFootball

The futuristic phenom. The sport sensation. Meet ‘Swooshman,’ arguably the greatest superhero in the history of superheroes. Swooshman’s legend began in the mid ‘90s when Nike’s Sport Entertainment division created a mascot that embodied the power, soul, and innovation of athletes everywhere. It was one of the most advanced mascot suits for the time, and made out of custom molded neoprene so the performer had full range of motion. The suit itself was designed in Hollywood by the same studio that made the suits for another very popular superhero 👀

These “Swooshman” artifacts have been supplied by the Department of Nike Archives.
